14/Nov/07 3:01 PM;712020:08ce5c32-3df2-47cc-8e3a-e1bbff771703;Not complicated at all...You just need to have correct version of TinyMCE ( =  2.1.2 ) , the version that comes with moodle does not work with Safari or Opera. Then you need to edit function can_use_html_editor in moodlelib.php and change that safari check from htmlarea.php + change functions print_textarea and use_html_editor to be able to use tinymce + have correct init settings for tinymce.
I have tested TinyMCE in moodle 1.6-1.9 using these changes and it works well with Safari in all modules. I have tested both weblib integration and theme integration but have not used editorlib at all. 

To make it simple use_html_editor does not have to contain anything (I have left this global $THEME; anyway) but you must have it somewhere and print_textarea is the function that replaces correct textareas (class form_textarea) with editor (TinyMCE). For example:

function use_html_editor($name='', $editorhidebuttons='', $id='') {
    global $THEME;
}
function print_textarea($usehtmleditor, $rows, $cols, $width, $height, $name, $value='', $courseid=0, $return=false, $id='') {
    global $CFG, $COURSE, $HTTPSPAGEREQUIRED;
    $str = '';
    if ($id === '') {
        $id = 'edit-'.$name;
    }
if (empty($courseid)) {
            $courseid = $COURSE->id;
        }
if ($usehtmleditor) {
    $str .= '<textarea class="form-textarea" id="'. $id .'" name="'. $name .'" rows="'. $rows .'" cols="'. $cols .'">';
    $str .= htmlspecialchars($value); 
    $str .= '</textarea>'."\n";
    $str .= '';
       }
else
{
    $str .= '<textarea class="alltext" id="'. $id .'" name="'. $name .'" rows="'. $rows .'" cols="'. $cols .'">';  
    $str .= s($value);
    $str .= '</textarea>'."\n";
}
    if ($return) {
        return $str;
    }
    echo $str;
}

It is a matter of taste if these functions are in weblib.php or theme files or some other place but TinyMCE needs also init code and usually it is in theme and if settings must be editable (as they will be in moodle...) init code should come from database or some file. I have written init code to theme header.html or meta.php (if I want to use standard theme or some parent theme to give same settings for several themes) to add for example following scripts just before </head> tag:

