03/Nov/11 4:23 AM;5ac1849f01b7457325cf62af;The problem has gone for most languages except zh-cn and zh-tw.

In Chinese culture, there is not a white space between first name and last name. For example, my name is , not  . Japanese and Korean are also in the same culture. But they add a space in moodle lang file for some reasons.

Long time ago, moodle began to use the following code to determine which name is first:

{code}
$nameordercheck = new stdClass();
$nameordercheck->firstname = 'a';
$nameordercheck->lastname  = 'b';
if (fullname($nameordercheck) == 'b a' ) {  // See MDL-4325
    $mform->addElement('text', 'lastname',  get_string('lastname'),  'maxlength="100" size="30"');
    $mform->addElement('text', 'firstname', get_string('firstname'), 'maxlength="100" size="30"');
} else {
    $mform->addElement('text', 'firstname', get_string('firstname'), 'maxlength="100" size="30"');
    $mform->addElement('text', 'lastname',  get_string('lastname'),  'maxlength="100" size="30"');
}
{code}

It assume that all lang have a space between first name and last name. So, it does not work for zh-cn and zh-tw.

I suggest that add a lib function, firstname_first(), to determine the order. The function should consider the white space case. Function like this is required in many places, such as MDL-26171, user/editlib.php

